Favorite app: I'd probably have to go with Obscura – It's a fairly straightforward camera app, but focuses on making manual controls easy to reach, with well curated filters. Focused on quality. Takes good pics.

My favorite aesthetic app right now is an app called Bumpers I'm beta testing. It's a short-form live podcasting app, essentially. I like the illustration style and "slime" aesthetic being used throughout. It gives the app a playful feel, but more importantly, gives it a visual branding – if you see a picture with some slime on it in the wild, you know it's a bumper.

1) Favorite general app that I would hate to note have is NYT Now. I find the constantly refreshing feed of only a limited amount of hand picked articles per day to be enough to keep me interested but not too much as to overwhelm me with an infinite feed of news.

2) I'm piggybacking on Melissa's Google Calendar choice. I love how the daily agenda view is so clean, sharp, and custom when it auto-uploads images for events with known locations. I also love that it intelligently uploads a nice illustration when it recognizes a specific event name, like jogging or weight lifting.

3) Honestly, I don't care about activity trackers outside of the compass project. But I'm throwing Argus into the mix because the design of it is interesting and even though I don't think it's entirely effective for what it's trying to achieve, it's very thoughtful in the way they've put it all together.

text: <@U02F8TTPU|marissa> has joined the channel

<@U02F8TTPU|marissa> uploaded a file: <https://uncorked.slack.com/files/marissa/F0M60KTK5/capture__2016-02-12-12-06-31.png|LEAF> and commented: I don't have a favorite overall app, but I think the LEAF tracker app is an excellent fitness app. It's updated frequently, and the visuals make me want to sync it every day even though I don't care about the metrics.

In this view, the up/down arrow is expanded, showing a calendar view that is H-scrollable and shows a summary of tracked activity on each day. The default view is not expanded. If you tap on the day or on an activity, you jump to a more detailed view. I like the color affinity and the UX is consciously designed -- touchable areas are intuitive and big.

<@U026E0ZNR|trent> uploaded a file: <https://uncorked.slack.com/files/trent/F0M646RQ9/slack_for_ios_upload.png|Slack for iOS Upload> and commented: I should probably mention Wokamon too since I've been playing it obsessively for nearly a month. It give me points for how many steps I take in a day, points that increase the amount of gems I can collect, which allow me to buy more Wokamon and dress them up like anthropomorphic Peter Pans and such. 

The game is highly absurd and shouldn't be worth my time but triggers all my addictive tendencies and keeps me coming back to see how many more points I got from the day's step count.

text: <@U0261PCRQ|kat> uploaded a file: <https://uncorked.slack.com/files/kat/F0M740X32/screenshot_2016-02-12-16-46-01.png|keep> and commented: I think I use keep more than any other app. I use it to remind myself to do things when I get home, or at a certain date/time. To remember recommendations for things and places to try. And I use it for grocery lists. I like that I can choose different colors for different topics and that they have different formats to choose from. Far from perfect, but it works for me.
